                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3kw5814t/manifest/annotation/p2",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>were it not for the School my income as<lb/> minister would not\n                                        keep me in board and lodging.<lb/> I am obliged to toil in\n                                        that laborious profession<lb/> as before, when, I hoped\n                                        that, after leaving <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>,<lb/> I\n                                        should not be again obliged to resume it.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">There is little or no improvement in<lb/>\n                                        spiritual matters. Sometimes, I am half inclined<lb/> to\n                                        blame myself as the cause of want of progress,<lb/> were the\n                                        character of the people not so well known.<lb/> There is too\n                                        much <add>Hebrew</add> here. It requires a being<lb/> of\n                                        greater capability than I possess to effect any\n                                        thorough<lb/> good. Thanks be to God we are quiet. I am\n                                        grateful<lb/> for small things in despair of accomplishing\n                                                  <add>?</add><lb/>\n                                        <add>?</add>. I have still<add>?</add> the rage for violent\n                                        changes,<lb/> and even our friend <persName>Wolff</persName>\n                                        is becoming orthodox.<lb/> The field of operation was better\n                                        in <placeName>Jamaica</placeName>. I shall<lb/> never affect\n                                        as much here as I did there. Still<lb/>\n                                        <persName>Carillon's</persName> mad schemes are silenced for\n                                        the <add>?</add>,<lb/> and the accomplishing so much is an\n                                        evidence<lb/> of the successful result of my ministry.\n                                        People<lb/> are more strict in pot and kettle than formerly\n                                        there<lb/> is good attendance at the Synagogues on\n                                        Sabbath,<lb/> and holy days, and the children generally are\n                                        learning<lb/> Hebrew, and religion. The girls generally are\n                                        studying<lb/> the sacred language, and several of them show\n                                        great<lb/> proficiency.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">A most <add>?</add> calamity has lately</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3kw5814t/canvas/p2"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
